		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			More of what I'd like to see:<br><br>- Ignore for X time. /ignore just simply ignores the target forever or until you delete your ini file. /ignore 30 ignores them for 30 minutes. /ignore 120 ignores them for 2 hours. Sometimes I need to ignore certain people for a short period of time, but don't want them ignored all the time. Such as guild-mates who hawk KEI and Virtue in the POK.<br><br>- I like the idea of a target lock. We already have one for group members, but this would be a super-bonus on raid situations, and/or wierd pull situations.<br><br>- Differentiated target ring for PCs, Pets, and NPCs. This would also work as a differentiated target ring that is determined by faction. Indiff or Dubious: all PCs and many NPCs would still be the plain, slightly hazy ring. Warmly or better is visibly different, as is threateningly or worse. You get a visual faction /consider without hitting /c. This would be helpful when grouping with a person who's using charm for crowd-control or DPS purposes. You wouldn't sit there and waste mana trying to damage a charm pet. Also, in crowded situations, it's often difficult to know if you have a friendly or an enemy targetted, even with the target ring. At a distance, it's exponentially worse. A mezzed creature might also get a different con ring. This might make a good leadership AA.<br><br>- The ability to name pets. God, I can't beleive no one (including myself) has brought this up as a UI issue.<br><br>- /who needs to return a definitive class name. /who all class already does this, but I often can't figure out what a 'Uberzapper 70 (Windstalker) ' is. Worse, he'll have a title like 'Apprentice Fletcher Uberzapper Mobripper' that says nothing about what he does in combat. Since we already have links in the text that go to items, why not make prestige classes linky too so we can click them and get a description?<br><br>If you click on 'Arch Lich' you'll get something similar to the text you get on character creation for the different classes:<br><br><b>Arch Lich</b><br>Necromancer level 65 or above.<br><br>Necromancers rely on their undead pets, powerful damage over time spells, and unique utility spells in order to defeat thier enemies. Necromancers often have trouble travelling to even the most tolerant of cities due to almost universal hate and distrust of their dark abilities'.<br><br>- Greater flexibility in the visual title system (This deserves its own post.)
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<hr><font size=-3 color="#666666">The less-organized group of 'casual' monkies are left wondering what's wrong. The levers are now so difficult to push, they're left eating the crumbs of old cookies and whatever comes flying across the room. The only time a Jolly Rancher comes their way, it's already covered in spit and monkey-hair. They're hungry. And their teeth hurt. They need their vitamins and some sweet monkey lovin', but the stench from the 'hard-core' side of the lab makes it difficult to get romantic.<br><br>Good God, won't somone give the casual monkies some dental floss?!</font>
							</div>
								
